ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the performance of the electrochemical-based sensing system toward bacteria, electrochemically generated CsWO3–FCD-coated Si wafers were exposed to various concentrations of bacteria and observed using an LCR meter and an EIS. The resistance before and after bacterial attachment to the surface of the CsWO3–FCD nanohybrids was determined (Fig. 5
                        ). Fig. 5a shows that FCD- and CsWO3–FCD-coated Si wafers displayed lower resistance values relative to bare and polymer-coated Si wafers, indicating that FCD and CsWO3 improved the conductivity of the coated surface. However, incubation of the CsWO3–FCD-coated Si wafers with bacteria markedly increased the resistance values owing to bacterial attachment to the coated surface. Moreover, a difference in resistance was observed between the bacteria-treated coated surfaces with and without washing after incubation (P < 0.01) with E. coli and S. aureus, respectively (Fig. 5b, c). This phenomenon occurred due to unattached bacteria remaining on the surface before washing, whereas after washing, the unattached bacteria were removed from the surface, resulting in decreased resistance. To confirm the effect of unattached bacteria on the change in resistance, bacteria were counted before and after washing using a flow cytometer (Table S1). We found that the number of bacteria decreased after washing, indicating the removal of unattached bacteria and confirming the cause of the decreased resistance. Furthermore, EIS measurement was performed upon the addition of bacteria (101–107 CFU/mL). We generated a Nyquist plot to measure frequency-dependent resistance in order to accurately distinguish small changes in resistance. The plot showed a significant difference in resistance corresponding to the increasing number of bacteria on the sensor surface (Fig. 6
                        a, b). These results revealed that increasing concentrations of bacteria corresponded to a greater number of bacterial cells attach on the surface, which generated a greater blocking effect on electron transfer [54].
